## A polished answer can still be the wrong answer

AI can produce work that looks finished very quickly. The type is large, the gradients glow, the cards are neatly rounded and something translucent floats in the background. At first glance it feels impressive. At second glance it may feel strangely familiar.

That familiarity is not always a problem. Design uses shared conventions because people need to understand what they are looking at. A button should not require an archaeological expedition. A checkout should not become performance art.

The problem begins when the fashionable answer becomes the automatic answer, regardless of the context. A healthcare organisation, a restaurant, a technology product and a cultural project all receive variations of the same visual treatment. The output looks current, but it has not listened closely enough.

This is where the idea of "trendslop" becomes useful. It gives a name to work that is polished and buzzy but weakly connected to the actual situation.

## Where the term came from

In March 2026, researchers Angelo Romasanta, Llewellyn D. W. Thomas and Natalia Levina discussed the term in a [Harvard Business Review article about LLM-generated strategic advice](https://hbr.org/2026/03/researchers-asked-llms-for-strategic-advice-they-got-trendslop-in-return). Their research concerned strategy rather than visual design. They found that models could recommend similar fashionable solutions even when the business context changed.

I am applying that idea to creative work because the same risk is easy to recognise. AI systems learn from patterns in existing material. When asked for a strong contemporary direction, they can reach for ideas that are already highly visible: the current layout, the current colour treatment, the current wording and the current definition of "premium".

This does not mean the tool is useless or dishonest. It means the model is doing what pattern-based systems often do. It gives us something statistically plausible. Context-specific judgement still has to come from the person directing and editing the work.

## Trends become a shortcut for relevance

Trends can be valuable. They reveal changes in technology, culture and audience expectations. Designers have always learned by looking at contemporary work. The trouble starts when looking becomes copying and relevance is reduced to surface style.

If every prompt includes the same references, every moodboard contains the same websites and every generated option uses the same effects, design begins to flatten. The projects may have different names, but they share the same visual accent.

AI increases this pressure because it can produce variations of a fashionable pattern instantly. One glass panel becomes twenty. One oversized serif becomes a complete brand system. The quantity creates an impression of exploration even when every option belongs to the same narrow family.

Real exploration should test different ideas about the problem. It should ask whether the tone needs to feel calm, urgent, warm, technical, familiar or challenging. It should consider what the audience already understands and what the organisation can maintain. Changing the gradient while keeping every assumption the same is not a strategic range.

## Taste is not just liking nice things

Taste is sometimes discussed as if it is a mysterious personal gift. Someone either has it or does not. That makes it sound impossible to examine and very convenient for anyone who wants the final say.

I see taste as a combination of judgement, context, restraint, references and editing. Personal preference is present, but it should not control everything.

Good taste in design includes recognising hierarchy, balance and proportion. It includes knowing when an unusual choice supports the idea and when it merely asks for attention. It includes understanding that a restrained solution can be more distinctive than a stack of fashionable effects.

It also includes knowing what to remove. This is one of the hardest skills to automate because generation naturally rewards addition. Ask for more impact and the answer often brings more colour, more scale, more motion and more objects. A designer may decide that impact comes from one confident image and a great deal of space around it.

Taste develops through exposure and practice. Look at design from different periods and disciplines. Study books, packaging, signage, architecture, film titles and ordinary functional objects. Follow work through production. Notice what ages well and what depends entirely on the fashion of its moment.

## Context should make the options less generic

A strong brief narrows the field in a useful way. It explains the audience, purpose, constraints and desired response. Those details should change the visual answer.

If the content is complex, the design may need exceptional hierarchy and calm. If the audience has limited time, the route through the information may need to be direct. If the organisation already has a trusted visual language, the job may be to extend it carefully rather than replace it with the latest aesthetic.

Production conditions matter too. A beautiful generated packaging concept may rely on materials the budget cannot support. A website animation may look impressive in a recording but feel slow on an average phone. A publication layout may collapse when the real copy arrives.

Context turns design from an image into a working decision. It gives us reasons to reject attractive options that are not appropriate.

## AI should expand the conversation

I am not interested in treating AI as a creative enemy. It can expand the range of material we consider. It can produce unexpected combinations, help visualise an early thought and make it cheaper to test an approach before investing heavily.

The useful position is somewhere between blind acceptance and automatic rejection.

I might ask a tool for several distinct directions, then question whether they are genuinely distinct. I can compare the results against the brief, identify the familiar shortcuts and push the exploration towards references outside the immediate trend cycle. I can combine a generated starting point with drawing, typography, photography, code or physical experimentation.

Most importantly, I can make the final decisions. AI can suggest. It should not quietly become the creative director because nobody wanted to edit the output.

## A practical trendslop check

When a generated direction looks polished, I find it useful to ask a few unfashionable questions.

Would this still make sense if the gradient disappeared? Could the same design be given to three unrelated clients without much change? Which decision comes directly from the brief? Is the hierarchy helping the audience or only creating a dramatic screenshot? Can the organisation produce and maintain it? What have we removed?

It also helps to compare alternatives side by side. AI output can feel convincing when viewed alone. Put several versions together and the repeated formula becomes easier to see.

Reconnect each choice to purpose. If a strong visual effect earns its place, keep it. If it exists because the tool has seen it everywhere, question it. Fashion is not automatically bad, but it should not be the only reason.

## Craft gives judgement evidence

Taste becomes stronger when it is connected to craft. Typography teaches proportion through real letters and real reading. Print teaches what happens when colour and material become physical. Packaging teaches constraint. Digital design teaches behaviour and responsiveness.

Those experiences give us evidence. We are not only saying that something feels wrong. We can explain that the line length is tiring, the contrast is weak, the interaction excludes touch users or the composition is competing with the content.

That explanation matters when working with AI because the quality of the next result depends partly on the quality of the direction. "Make it better" invites another fashionable guess. A clear critique creates a more useful iteration.

## More options make editing more valuable

The age of AI is not short of visual material. The shortage is attention, judgement and the willingness to stop.

As generation becomes faster, creative value moves towards framing the problem, selecting references, comparing options and refining the result. Taste matters because it helps us decide what deserves to remain.

Avoiding trendslop does not require avoiding trends or technology. It requires curiosity beyond the current feed, a clear connection to the brief and enough confidence to remove a fashionable idea when it is not doing useful work.

AI can widen the field. Craft and taste help us choose a direction worth following.
